### Version

Yosys 0.53+3 (git sha1 6378ba10e, clang++ 14.0.0-1ubuntu1.1 -fsanitize=address -fPIC -O3 -O1 -fno-omit-frame-pointer -fno-optimize-sibling-calls -fsanitize=address,undefined)

### On which OS did this happen?

Linux

### Reproduction Steps

The issue may be similar to the root cause of [https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/issues/5099](https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/issues/5099) (an integer overflow somewhere).

Here is the code (`test.v`) that triggers the issue:

```verilog
module top (
    output wire out1,
    output wire out2,
);
    wire signed wire_1 = 1'b1;
    assign out1 = wire_1 >>> 36'hfffffffff;
    assign out2 = wire_1 >>> 36'hfffffff;
endmodule
```

Run the following command to perform optimization:

```
yosys -p "read_verilog test.v; opt; write_verilog opt.v"
```

The optimized output (`opt.v`) is:

```verilog
/* Generated by Yosys 0.53+3 (git sha1 6378ba10e, clang++ 14.0.0-1ubuntu1.1 -fsanitize=address -fPIC -O3 -O1 -fno-omit-frame-pointer -fno-optimize-sibling-calls -fsanitize=address,undefined) */

(* cells_not_processed =  1  *)
(* src = "test.v:1.1-9.10" *)
module top(out1, out2);
  (* src = "test.v:2.17-2.21" *)
  output out1;
  wire out1;
  (* src = "test.v:3.17-3.21" *)
  output out2;
  wire out2;
  (* src = "test.v:5.17-5.23" *)
  wire wire_1;
  assign out1 = 1'h0;
  assign out2 = 1'h1;
  assign wire_1 = 1'h1;
endmodule
```

As you can see, `out1` and `out2` produce different results.

I’ve already applied the patch from [https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/pull/5101](https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/pull/5101) and tested it with similar code like `assign out1 = (in >> 36'hfffffffff)`, but the issue still persists. Therefore, I suspect there may be an integer overflow specifically when handling the `>>>` operator.


### Expected Behavior

Both `out1` and `out2` should be `1` after the shift operation.



### Actual Behavior

`out1` is incorrectly optimized to `0`, while `out2` is correctly `1`.

